               <p>ANDREW DUNN. I am a <rs id="t18281023-115-viclabel684" type="occupation">journeyman baker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281023-115-victim672 t18281023-115-viclabel684"></join>, in the employ of Mr. Harvey. I was in the street on the 16th of October, and left my barrow while I went round the <placeName id="t18281023-115-crimeloc685">Regent's-park</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18281023-115-crimeloc685" type="placeName" value="Regent's-park"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18281023-115-crimeloc685" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281023-115-off682 t18281023-115-crimeloc685"></join>, about half a mile - I left it in charge of a person who is not here: when I came back, the beadle asked me to look, and I missed three loaves; the prisoner was then in custody.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281023-115-person673">
                  JAMES 
                  McINTOSH
               <interp inst="t18281023-115-person673" type="surname" value="McINTOSH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-115-person673" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-115-person673" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. The prisoner was walking about the different streets, and I rather suspected him; he went near the Trinity church, and I saw him lift up the sack from the basket which was on the barrow, and take out three loaves and walk away; I and another man took him into custody.</p>

               <p>The prisoner pleaded distress, and received a good character.</p>
